<DOC><DOCNO> AP890404-0211 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-89 0128EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     04-04 0750</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0786</SECOND><DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. USA saysit will spend $490 million to expand its auto plant into one of thebiggest in the country and create 2,000 jobs.   A new model to be made at the plant will be a four-door,family-sized car pitched to the same market as the Nissan Stanza,the company said Monday.   The plant produces 240,000 Sentras and light trucks a year. Theproduction of the new car will boost the total output to 440,000vehicles by 1992.</TEXT><DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chrysler Corp. has begun offeringinterest-free, two-year loans on all of its cars and some lighttrucks, in an escalation of the latest round of buyer incentivesfrom the automakers.   The move Monday came after Ford Motor Co. dropped its interestrate for 24-month loans to 2.9 percent last Wednesday. GeneralMotors Corp. followed that lead a day later.</TEXT><DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three former defense contractingexecutives heard themselves accused of ``bribing ... cheating ...lying'' at the start of the first trial stemming from the federalinvestigation into fraud in the Pentagon's purchasing system.   The defendants' lawyers said Monday they had done nothing wrong.   The three former Teledyne Electronics executives _ George Kaub,Dale Schnittjer and Eugene Sullivan _ are charged with bribery,conspiracy and making false statements.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Construction spending was nearly flat inFebruary as a small increase in government projects was offset byslower work on housing and other non-government buildings, theCommerce Department says.   February's performance was the weakest since constructionspending declined 0.2 percent last August, the department saidMonday. Analysts said rising interest rates and caution about theeconomic outlook were holding back building activity.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Consumer confidence dropped in March asAmericans grew more concerned about rising interest rates, theConference Board says.   The organization said Monday its consumer confidence index fellto 117.7, down from 120.7 in February. The index has a base of 100.   Despite the drop, the index remained at a relatively high level,noted Fabian Linden, an economist with the business-supportedresearch group.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An insurance group says it will stop providingadvisory insurance rates, a step it said will increase costs toinsurance companies and state governments but should not affectpolicyholders.   The Insurance Services Office Inc. said Monday it dropped theadvisory rates in response to consumer groups' accusations thatthey were akin to price-fixing.   Instead, the group will provide its 1,400 participatingcompanies only with estimates of future loss payments.</TEXT><DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Exxon apologized for causing the nation'sbiggest oil spill and promised to clean up every fouled beach inPrince William Sound, but workers on those greasy-smelling beachessaid their efforts are futile.   Police continued Monday searching for the captain of the tankerExxon Valdez, which crashed into Bligh Reef on March 24. The oilslick has grown larger than Rhode Island.   Meanwhile, Exxon Corp.'s president says he hopes the ``emotionaltype of atmosphere'' generated by the spill does not promptCongress to reject the oil industry's request to drill in protectedwildlife areas.   In an interview Monday, President Lee R. Raymond also sought todispel speculation that Exxon was profiting from the spill throughhigher oil prices, or that the accident stemmed partly fromcost-reducing safety shortcuts.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A committee representing unsecured creditors ofEastern Airlines is asking those interested in buying thestrikebound carrier to present their offers at a meeting Tuesday,union and airline sources say.   Union sources also said Monday the Air Line Pilots Associationhas agreed to meet in the next few days with possible Easternsuitor Jay Pritzker, head of the Hyatt Corp. hotel chain.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   Stock prices staged a moderate advance Monday as the secondquarter of the year opened to a barrage of takeover news andrumors. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 11.18 to2,304.80.   The dollar, tamed by a declaration of unity among the majorindustrial nations, declined in domestic and overseas trading.   Bond prices strengthened, although they were knocked off theirhighs of the day by central bank action to knock down the dollar.   Crude oil futures declined after near-normal activities resumedat the Valdez, Alaska, port, which was partially blocked after arecent oil spill. Most grain and livestock futures prices closedmostly lower, while precious metals prices were mostly higher.</TEXT></DOC>